    "score": 7,
    "featured": false,
    "excerpt": "Possession is undeniably extraordinary. It is also absolutely exhausting, and whether that is a compliment depends entirely on what you are looking for.",
    "body": [
      "Andrzej Zulawski's Possession from 1981 is not a film you watch so much as survive. A disintegrating marriage in Cold War Berlin, an alien entity in a Warsaw flat, Isabelle Adjani doing things in a subway tunnel that should not be physically possible. There is craft here that cannot be denied. Zulawski shoots West Berlin with a grey, suffocating weight that makes every frame feel like a threat. The direction is restless and aggressive in a way that reads as intentional rather than sloppy, which matters a great deal. Sam Neill is doing strong work as a man unravelling under circumstances he cannot categorise. And then there is Adjani. The subway sequence is the kind of performance that makes you wonder what it cost her. It is total dissolution and genuinely difficult to watch. That is a compliment.",
      "The problem with Possession is that it is also aggressively, deliberately exhausting in ways that are not always rewarding. The symbolism is dense and Zulawski is not interested in guiding you through it. Some of the tonal lurches feel more chaotic than controlled, which the film's defenders would call deliberate. Maybe. But deliberate chaos and uncontrolled chaos look very similar from the inside and I cannot always tell which one I am watching. The first act demands a patience that not every viewer will have and I understand completely why people bounce off this film. It mistakes intensity for depth in certain stretches and the line between committed art cinema and wilful alienation gets blurry in the middle sections.",
      "Possession rewards the viewers it is designed for and punishes everyone else, which is a legitimate artistic choice I respect more than I enjoy. The creature effects in the second half are extraordinary for 1981. I came out of this thinking about it, which counts. I also came out of it genuinely drained in a way that did not feel entirely intentional. Watch it once, give it the uncut version and your full attention, and accept that whether it clicks for you will depend entirely on your tolerance for cinema that treats your discomfort as the point."
    ],
    "images": [],
    "verdict": "Possession is a genuinely singular piece of filmmaking with a performance from Adjani that has no equal, but its relentless intensity tips into self-punishment enough times to keep it from the top tier. 7/10.",
