    "id": 1780232272863,
    "slug": "late-night-with-the-devil-review",
    "category": "movie",
    "title": "Late Night with the Devil",
    "year": 2023,
    "director": "Cameron Cairnes, Colin Cairnes",
    "runtime": "93 min",
    "rating": "R",
    "genres": [
      "Horror",
      "Found Footage",
      "Supernatural"
    ],
    "score": 9,
    "featured": false,
    "excerpt": "Late Night with the Devil pulls off something most horror films spend their whole runtime trying to do and still fail. It actually got me.",
    "body": [
      "Colin and Cameron Cairnes built something special with Late Night with the Devil in 2023. The premise is tight and exactly right: a struggling 1970s late night talk show host films a Halloween special in 1977 that goes catastrophically wrong, and we are watching the recovered broadcast footage decades later. That framing device does real work. The period detail is immaculate, the talk show format is authentic enough to be properly unsettling rather than costumey, and the atmosphere the Cairnes brothers build through it, awkward pauses, wrong smiles, a live studio audience that laughs when it should not, is some of the most effective slow burn horror I have seen in recent years. It earns its dread through format before it earns it through anything supernatural, which is the smarter choice and the harder one to pull off.",
      "David Dastmalchian is the reason this works as well as it does. He carries the whole film on his back with a performance that walks the line between charming and deeply wrong with total precision. Jack Delroy is performing for his audience on screen and Dastmalchian is performing for us, and the layers of that double performance are exactly what the film needs. When things start to genuinely break down in the final act the shift feels earned rather than imposed, because he has been laying the groundwork for it from the first scene. The practical work in the later sequences is strong and there are images here that will stay with you. The AI generated interstitial cards caused real controversy at release and the criticism is fair. It is a strange choice that chips away at craft that is otherwise fully committed. Minor complaint against something firing on almost every cylinder.",
      "Late Night with the Devil does what very few horror films actually manage: it builds to something and then delivers it. The final act does not pull its punches and the commitment to going all the way with the premise is exactly what separates this from the found footage films that set up well and then flinch. It is on Shudder and various streaming platforms and it deserves to be talked about in the same breath as Host and REC as found footage that actually knows what it is doing. One of the best horror films of 2023 and it is not particularly close."
    ],
    "images": [],
    "media": {
      "poster": "https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZDZjMWI4NWEtMWIyMS00MWU4LWIwMzktMjc2NDZjYzM3YzhmXkEyXkFqcGc@._V1_FMjpg_UX1000_.jpg",
      "backdrop": "https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BZDZjMWI4NWEtMWIyMS00MWU4LWIwMzktMjc2NDZjYzM3YzhmXkEyXkFqcGc@._V1_FMjpg_UX1000_.jpg"
    },
    "verdict": "Late Night with the Devil is an exceptional found footage horror with a career performance from Dastmalchian and the courage to fully commit to its premise. One small AI controversy aside, this is the best the subgenre has offered in years. 9/10."
